1
00:00:02,173 --> 00:00:31,152
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:33,594 --> 00:00:37,822
So we can continue our little exploration of the Dhammapada.

3
00:00:38,042 --> 00:00:46,676
I've chosen a set of verses, 88 to 92, and they're all to do with taking refugees' confidence.

4
00:00:47,356 --> 00:00:50,843
So I shall do my usual thing of intoning them.

5
00:00:53,387 --> 00:00:58,454
Bhāhuṁ vā saraṇāṁ yānti pabhābhate na vālānīca

6
00:00:58,942 --> 00:01:26,281
harama rukkha chaitiyani manusabhayatta jitta netanko saranam kemang netang saranam uttamang netang saranam aggama sabba dukkha pamuchyati yuca budhamsa damamsa sangamsa saranam gato chatthari arya sacchani samma panyaya pasati

7
00:01:27,022 --> 00:01:55,171
This one's easy because it's very straightforward really.

8
00:01:55,405 --> 00:01:57,106
So this is a translation.

9
00:01:59,730 --> 00:02:05,737
People threatened by fear go to many refuges, to mountains, forests, parks, trees and shrines.

10
00:02:06,599 --> 00:02:08,581
None of these are a secure refuge.

11
00:02:09,082 --> 00:02:10,844
None is a supreme refuge.

12
00:02:11,746 --> 00:02:15,211
Not by going to such refuge is one released from all suffering.

13
00:02:16,412 --> 00:02:24,923
Having gone for refuge to the Buddha, Dhamma, Sangha, they see with right view the Four Noble Truths, suffering, the arising of suffering,

14
00:02:25,358 --> 00:02:30,203
the overcoming of suffering and the eightfold noble path leading to the end of suffering.

15
00:02:31,123 --> 00:02:32,905
This is the secure refuge.

16
00:02:33,104 --> 00:02:34,926
This is the supreme refuge.

17
00:02:35,448 --> 00:02:40,532
By going to such refuge, one is released from all suffering."

18
00:02:40,552 --> 00:02:52,563
So these verses were chanted by the Buddha when he came across a certain, excuse me, a certain character called Adjidatta.

19
00:03:00,256 --> 00:03:02,899
So this is the story that it hangs on.

20
00:03:03,721 --> 00:03:09,367
Adjidatta was the head priest during the time of King Mahakosala, father of King Pasenadi.

21
00:03:09,848 --> 00:03:13,973
King Pasenadi was a great supporter of the Buddha and was the king of Kosala.

22
00:03:15,014 --> 00:03:24,508
After the death of King Mahakosala, Adjidatta gave away all his property in charity and after that he left home and became a non-Buddhist ascetic.

23
00:03:25,348 --> 00:03:36,501
He lived with his 10,000 followers in a place near the border of three kingdoms, Anga, Magadha and Kuru, not far from the mound of sand where a powerful Naga was staying.

24
00:03:37,100 --> 00:03:45,830
Now a Naga is a combination of a divine being or even a human being and a snake or a serpent.

25
00:03:46,591 --> 00:03:54,900
And it was the Nagas that kept the Mahayana scriptures hidden until it was time for them to be discovered or revealed rather.

26
00:03:57,731 --> 00:04:27,350
and and these nagas are worshipped all over southeast asia i'm not so sure now but in those times it's not just a buddhist thing but the famous one for a buddhist is of course musilanda so musilanda was the um the cobra who came and and uh and protected the buddha from the heavy rains um a deluge came down just after his enlightenment so i presume it was the start of the rainy season and musilanda rose up and uh

27
00:04:28,072 --> 00:04:32,639
His cobra cover helped the Buddha from getting soaked.

28
00:04:33,178 --> 00:04:35,742
I actually have a very regular copy of that.

29
00:04:36,202 --> 00:04:40,588
That is a picture of the Naga.

30
00:04:41,088 --> 00:04:42,850
He's got a few heads there.

31
00:04:43,911 --> 00:04:44,874
I don't quite know why.

32
00:04:44,913 --> 00:04:47,956
And the Buddha looks tremendously serene.

33
00:04:48,598 --> 00:04:49,959
So he's doing all right.

34
00:04:51,841 --> 00:04:52,882
It's a great old statue.

35
00:04:52,923 --> 00:04:55,887
I don't know where it came from or who gave it to us.

36
00:04:57,452 --> 00:05:00,815
So that's the Naga and he lived on this sandpit.

37
00:05:02,517 --> 00:05:12,949
Now, one day the Buddha saw Ajitata and his followers in his vision and realized that the time was right for them to attain Arahatship.

38
00:05:13,528 --> 00:05:24,000
So the Buddha sent the Mahatera Moggallana, that's remember his second great disciple who was Sariputta Moggallana and Moggallana is the one known for

39
00:05:24,216 --> 00:05:27,439
these special powers.

40
00:05:30,002 --> 00:05:36,387
So Moggallana went to Ajitata and then the Buddha said he'd follow afterwards.

41
00:05:37,149 --> 00:05:43,454
So when Moggallana went to the place of Ajitata and his followers asked him, asked them to give him shelter for one night.

42
00:05:44,254 --> 00:05:50,680
They first turned down his request, but finally they agreed to let him stop at the mound of sand, the home of the Naga.

43
00:05:51,461 --> 00:05:53,142
The Naga was very antagonistic.

44
00:05:53,747 --> 00:05:56,432
and there followed a duel between the Naga and the Tera.

45
00:05:56,752 --> 00:06:02,560
On both sides, there was a display of power by emitting smokes and flames.

46
00:06:03,341 --> 00:06:05,564
However, in the end, the Naga was subdued.

47
00:06:06,045 --> 00:06:15,218
He coiled himself round the mound of sand, raised his head, spreading it out like an umbrella over the Mahatera, thus showing respect for him.

48
00:06:15,980 --> 00:06:22,810
Early in the morning, Ajidatta and the other ascetics came to the mound of sand to find out whether Mahatera was still alive.

49
00:06:23,177 --> 00:06:25,120
They had expected him to be dead.

50
00:06:25,901 --> 00:06:33,471
When they found the Naga tame and meekly holding his head like an umbrella over Moggallana, they were very much astounded.

51
00:06:34,331 --> 00:06:41,519
Just then, the Buddha arrived, and Mahamoggallana got up from his seat on the mount and paid obeisance to the Buddha.

52
00:06:42,562 --> 00:06:51,091
Mahamoggallana then proclaimed to the audience of ascetics, this is my teacher, the Supreme Buddha, and I am but a humble pupil of this great teacher.

53
00:06:51,882 --> 00:06:59,836
Hearing him, the ascetics, who had been very much impressed even by the power of Bhagavan, were awed by the greater power of the Buddha.

54
00:07:00,677 --> 00:07:09,093
The Buddha then asked Adjidatta when he taught his followers and the residents of the neighbourhood what he taught them.

55
00:07:09,634 --> 00:07:16,505
Adjidatta replied that he had taught them to pay homage to the mountains, forests, parks, gardens and trees.

56
00:07:16,958 --> 00:07:20,581
and that by doing so they would be liberated from all ills of life.

57
00:07:20,922 --> 00:07:24,565
So I presume he was what we would call a pagan, I suppose.

58
00:07:25,146 --> 00:07:33,473
It wouldn't have been just, it's funny, in those days they would have presumed that the devas were around these particular places.

59
00:07:35,836 --> 00:07:46,307
And the Buddha replied to Ajidatta, Ajidatta, people go to the mountains, forests, gardens and parks and trees for refuge when they are threatened with danger, but these things cannot offer them any protection.

60
00:07:46,810 --> 00:07:52,317
Only those who've taken refuge in the Buddha Dhamma Sangha are liberated from the rounds of rebirth.

61
00:07:52,716 --> 00:07:57,562
At the end of the discourse, Adjidatta and all his followers attained Arahatship.

62
00:07:58,384 --> 00:08:00,427
All of them entered the order of the bhikkhus.

63
00:08:01,127 --> 00:08:15,264
On that day, when the disciples of Adjidatta from Anga, Magadha and Kuru came to pay respects to him, they saw their teacher and his followers garbed as bhikkhus and they were puzzled and wondered, who is the more powerful?

64
00:08:15,785 --> 00:08:18,028
our teacher or the Samana Gautama.

65
00:08:18,769 --> 00:08:24,035
Our teacher must be more powerful because Samana Gautama came to our teacher.

66
00:08:25,377 --> 00:08:26,999
The Buddha knew what they were thinking.

67
00:08:27,338 --> 00:08:30,283
Ajita also felt that he must set their minds at rest.

68
00:08:30,744 --> 00:08:39,193
So he paid obeisance to the Buddha in the presence of his disciples and said, venerable sir, you are my teacher, I am but a disciple of yours.

69
00:08:39,554 --> 00:08:43,799
Thus the audience came to realize the supremacy of the Buddha.

70
00:08:44,793 --> 00:08:48,818
So there we have a nice little story to support our verses.

71
00:08:50,841 --> 00:09:04,681
I always find it rather amusing that the Naga and Moggallana were spitting fire and fumes of smoke on this mound which can't have been that far away from Anjidatta.

72
00:09:05,261 --> 00:09:11,070
How they slept through the commotion is itself a magical effort.

73
00:09:11,759 --> 00:09:18,086
So anyway, what I really want to just dwell on a little bit is the crucial role of confidence.

74
00:09:18,888 --> 00:09:35,067
So, you know, just if you sometimes reflect back on your life and remember the first time that you, the first day that you started your job, your first work, that of course you were confident, but you weren't entirely confident.

75
00:09:35,873 --> 00:09:42,119
It was only after being there for a while, knowing what the work actually involved, that the confidence grew.

76
00:09:42,158 --> 00:09:47,945
So here, through the experience, and of course, the knowledge that came as you're doing it.

77
00:09:49,046 --> 00:09:54,030
So here you have this combination of confidence and experience.

78
00:09:56,273 --> 00:10:04,902
And if you look at, if you think about a relationship, how long did it, I mean, the confidence was there at the beginning,

79
00:10:05,049 --> 00:10:32,727
an intimate relationship but then how long did it take you know for there to be enough confidence for you know to establish a an intimate relationship to establish either a partnership or a marriage so those that again is to do with experience is to do with you know going through what you had intended to do but without that confidence you would never have started

80
00:10:33,129 --> 00:10:44,379
If you take a very simple example, like jumping off the high board, uh, I do remember starting off on the springboard and then, and then moving up to the first level of the high board.

81
00:10:44,399 --> 00:10:47,923
And then finally I got to the top and it was a jump.

82
00:10:47,982 --> 00:10:51,767
I never quite got around to diving head first into the water.

83
00:10:52,626 --> 00:10:54,389
So I lacked confidence there.

84
00:10:55,710 --> 00:11:00,514
So you can see competencies is that it's at the basis at the root of anything we do.

85
00:11:00,614 --> 00:11:01,315
In fact, uh,

86
00:11:01,732 --> 00:11:09,443
You know, you wouldn't lift your cup of tea to your mouth if you didn't have confidence that it would actually arrive there, you know.

87
00:11:13,428 --> 00:11:25,787
And it's one of the, what we call the faculties, spiritual faculties, which runs normally in tandem with paññā, with insight and wisdom.

88
00:11:26,287 --> 00:11:30,373
So this combination of confidence, practice,

89
00:11:30,657 --> 00:11:34,100
and experience, the one supports the other.

90
00:11:34,600 --> 00:11:45,493
And at some point, if a person has a deep enough insight to enter the first path and fruit, this quality becomes a bala, a power.

91
00:11:45,572 --> 00:11:53,961
You could say it's unshakable because now they realize by their own direct experience that in fact, there is an end to suffering.

92
00:11:54,263 --> 00:11:59,128
Even if it's only dimly seen, they have that absolute confidence.

93
00:11:59,259 --> 00:12:03,583
Now here's a little something that came to mind when I was thinking about this.

94
00:12:04,424 --> 00:12:13,274
In Islam, if you are asked to deny your religion and your life is in danger, you can do so.

95
00:12:14,215 --> 00:12:21,582
So when the Inquisition in Spain demanded that they all become baptised, they were able to do so.

96
00:12:21,942 --> 00:12:27,388
Outwardly, they were Christians, but inwardly, of course, they remained Muslims.

97
00:12:27,408 --> 00:12:28,929
If you contrast that with

98
00:12:29,298 --> 00:12:39,214
Christianity, which begins, of course, with the story of Peter, who denies Christ and really feels, and of course, Judas, who then hangs himself.

99
00:12:39,313 --> 00:12:47,006
But Jesus, you know, Peter must have felt terribly embarrassed having denied his teacher.

100
00:12:47,687 --> 00:12:51,673
And so what we get in Christianity is much more an acceptance of martyrdom.

101
00:12:52,576 --> 00:12:56,621
And even, you know, when the Inquisition moved to

102
00:12:56,938 --> 00:13:26,119
southern france and started chasing the cathars the illuminati and in fact i think just ordinary cathars they actually threw themselves onto the bonfires onto the yeah onto the fire i went to one place um i couldn't find the name of it but what happened was there were about 150 of cathars who may have all been illuminati i don't know but um they actually threw themselves onto the bonfire

103
00:13:26,774 --> 00:13:54,267
so a very different attitude and of course you wouldn't do that if you didn't have absolute confidence that you were righteous and that you would be reborn in heaven and that the you know you wouldn't be just jumping out of one fire into the fires of hell just a nice little little aside there so of course what do we mean when we say we take the refugees well

104
00:13:54,583 --> 00:14:00,091
In terms of the Buddha, of course, it's just a confidence in him as our teacher.

105
00:14:00,472 --> 00:14:02,655
But it's also, again, his practice.

106
00:14:03,057 --> 00:14:07,302
We know what he went through to become liberated.

107
00:14:07,783 --> 00:14:09,486
And that, of course, gives us a confidence.

108
00:14:09,606 --> 00:14:12,211
It's not as though he just appeared and said, do this and do that.

109
00:14:13,293 --> 00:14:15,075
He actually went through it himself.

110
00:14:15,216 --> 00:14:22,667
So his teaching comes directly out of his own experience.

111
00:14:23,018 --> 00:14:37,163
If you find yourself to be a devotional type, then you know the whole idea of reading about, excuse me, the whole idea about reading about his life and his story and contemplating that.

112
00:14:37,825 --> 00:14:42,573
And of course, the idea is that you say to yourself, may I be like the Buddha.

113
00:14:42,734 --> 00:14:46,139
So there's a connection there of wanting to imitate the Buddha.

114
00:14:47,673 --> 00:14:53,541
But I think we also have to take the refuge within ourselves.

115
00:14:53,620 --> 00:14:54,743
There's a Buddha within us.

116
00:14:55,182 --> 00:14:56,524
We just haven't realized it yet.

117
00:14:57,225 --> 00:15:05,496
And it's actually putting confidence that is in us, that which is seeking its own liberation from suffering.

118
00:15:06,378 --> 00:15:13,307
So I think that's an important aside, which is normally not included in the refuges and precepts.

119
00:15:13,827 --> 00:15:17,173
But I just think acknowledging that is important.

120
00:15:18,351 --> 00:15:22,138
The Dharma, of course, is the teaching and the practice itself.

121
00:15:22,938 --> 00:15:27,365
And it's normally put as three types of knowledges.

122
00:15:27,426 --> 00:15:32,232
The first one is that when you hear the teaching, you may be inspired by it.

123
00:15:33,073 --> 00:15:35,577
And then you have to sort of make it your own teaching.

124
00:15:35,597 --> 00:15:39,464
And that's when you sort of mull over it, where you ponder the teachings.

125
00:15:39,803 --> 00:15:42,388
And that leads you to a certain practice.

126
00:15:43,048 --> 00:15:46,674
And what you learn actually becomes your own real experience.

127
00:15:46,695 --> 00:15:47,615
And that's vipassana.

128
00:15:48,288 --> 00:15:58,644
So there are these three levels that are pointed at when it comes to our understanding of Buddhism.

129
00:15:58,703 --> 00:16:06,315
It starts with just that reading, hearing, and then finally moves to our own direct experience.

130
00:16:06,816 --> 00:16:12,303
None of that could happen were it not that the confidence is slowly building up over time.

131
00:16:16,654 --> 00:16:23,947
Now these refuges that we take, they weren't actually part of the original refuges that the monastics took.

132
00:16:24,508 --> 00:16:33,503
When he first started, the first people who sort of approached him and said, look, you know, I'd like, I'd like to follow your teachings, you know, could you be my teacher?

133
00:16:34,244 --> 00:16:38,991
His response was just, ahi passico, which just means come and try, have a go, see what happens.

134
00:16:41,155 --> 00:16:42,357
Later on when he had,

135
00:16:42,625 --> 00:16:58,601
established some of his disciples as Arahats, that's when this taking refuge in him and in the teachings and in the Sangha came in for anybody who wanted to become a monastic.

136
00:16:59,322 --> 00:17:10,354
However, in time of course, well they say about after 20 years, people who joined the order weren't of a high caliber and they started doing naughty things and so

137
00:17:10,502 --> 00:17:38,906
rules had to be made all sorts of rules that go i go from obviously moral law such as uh you know thieving and murder and all that sort of stuff but go down to very minute behavior so that for instance when i'm eating i'm not supposed to make chapu chapu sounds or suru suru sounds i'm not supposed to be making sounds as i chew or slurping my drink

138
00:17:39,393 --> 00:17:44,361
So even that sort of very basic etiquette is part of the rule.

139
00:17:46,042 --> 00:17:58,402
So now what happened was as lay people came to want to be his disciples, that second tier of commitment, Buddha Dhamma Sangha, became the lay ordination.

140
00:17:58,541 --> 00:17:59,884
That's how it moved.

141
00:18:00,164 --> 00:18:03,509
That's how it's become the lay ordination.

142
00:18:06,763 --> 00:18:34,037
and uh there's all sorts of levels of commitment um you know when i became a monk um or i came back to the east to the west came back to the west um i began daily shaving my head in the east i would do it every two weeks that's a normal time just before you go in for the veneer

143
00:18:34,844 --> 00:19:04,023
the patimokha where the vineyard is read out you see and uh but here in when i return to the west i determined to shave my head every day just to remind myself that i am actually a monk it was my morning ritual uh nothing nothing catastrophic happens if i miss shaving my head uh but it's just there as a little practice in the morning and that's why uh you know taking breakfast and precepts is is something that

144
00:19:04,425 --> 00:19:07,671
We try to make fairly habitual every morning.

145
00:19:08,111 --> 00:19:17,684
It doesn't take long, but it's just a moment where you remind yourself of your practice, of what your life is ultimately about.

146
00:19:18,727 --> 00:19:24,375
And it's just those little reminders every day that just keep pumping the energy into your practice.

147
00:19:27,982 --> 00:19:30,705
So that's it really.

148
00:19:30,885 --> 00:19:41,134
The question is, you know, as a sort of contemplation is, you know, what is the role of confidence in my life and how can I make it grow?

149
00:19:41,174 --> 00:19:43,817
You know, how do I increase this confidence?

150
00:19:44,258 --> 00:19:46,099
Various ways in which I can do it.

151
00:19:48,801 --> 00:19:55,087
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused even greater confusion.

152
00:19:55,355 --> 00:20:02,614
and that by your devotion to the practice you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

